[3] Pakistan: vaccine refusals, media report
Date: Fri 22 Feb 2019
Source: The Nation [edited]
https://nation.com.pk/22-Feb-2019/several-parents-refuse-to-administer-anti-polio-drops-to-children


Parents of scores of children have reportedly refused polio vaccination for their offspring during the ongoing anti-polio campaign in Rawalpindi. The refusal cases were reported in several streets of Munawar Colony, a thickly populated area located on Adiala Road and controlled by Police Station (PS) Saddar Bairooni. Official sources disclosed to The Nation on Thursday [21 Feb 2019] that scores of parents have stopped the anti-polio teams from administering polio drops to their children during an ongoing anti-polio campaign in Munawar Colony. They said the anti-polio teams have also been threatened by the family heads when they tried to convince them for allowing them to put polio drops in mouths of children under age 5 years old, they said.

Sources said the anti-polio teams have brought the matter into notice of district government authorities. A meeting is expected to be held soon under the chair of DeC in this regard. The authorities would evolve a plan to approach and convince parents who did not allow health workers to administer polio drops to their children, sources said.

Talking to The Nation, a female health visitor said the families residing in streets bordering with Global and Roots Schools opposite Dhama Mor have refused to allow polio drops to be administered to their children. "Don't visit and knock our door ever as you administer polio drops with dirty hands that may put the lives of our children into danger," the lady health worker quoted a family head as saying. When contacted, DC Muhammad Ali Randhawa said the parents are not allowed legally for refusing the polio teams from administering polio drops to children.

He said he would send the senior polio workers and the assistant commissioner to the area for counselling with the families. He also said adequate security would be provided to the polio teams and that the aim of district government was at to make Rawalpindi a polio-free city.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This media report above presents a glimpse of the challenges facing Pakistan in terms of interrupting transmission of the WPV. In addition to this report of refusals in Rawalpindi, there has been widespread media coverage of a famous Pakistani actor whose wife allegedly refused to vaccinate their child and his being charged for the incident (see https://tribune.com.pk/story/1915477/4-fawad-khan-speaks-amid-polio-controversy/). While the child in question is apparently adequately vaccinated, it doesn't help the national program efforts to have such media coverage suggesting they support non-vaccination. - Mod.MPP]
